        body: "A standby stays a standby only until something tells it to stop replaying and start accepting writes of its own, and that transition — promotion — has to be triggered explicitly: an administrator issues pg_ctl promote at the shell, or an already-connected session calls the pg_promote() SQL function directly against the standby. Right before making that switch, the server finishes replaying whatever WAL is already sitting locally, in its archive or its pg_wal directory, but it makes no further attempt to reach out to the old primary for anything more recent — once promotion begins, that connection is treated as irrelevant going forward. Not every standby needs this at all: a reporting replica that exists purely to soak up read-only analytical queries, with no intention of ever becoming a write target, can simply stay in standby mode indefinitely rather than ever being promoted. Once promotion does happen for an HA-oriented standby, though, it's expected to take over primary duties in full, including archiving and accepting its own new set of standby connections.",
