        title: 'A Taxonomy of Replication and HA Approaches',
        body: "Streaming and logical replication are PostgreSQL's own built-in answers, but they sit within a much broader family of techniques, each trading off performance, granularity, and failure guarantees differently. Shared-disk failover sidesteps synchronization entirely by having every server point at one physical disk array, which trades a single point of storage failure for zero replication overhead. File-system-level (block device) replication, with DRBD being a well-known Linux example, mirrors every disk write to a second machine below the database layer, so it needs no PostgreSQL-specific support but requires writes to land on the mirror in the same order they hit the primary. WAL shipping — this domain's own streaming and file-based replication — only ever works at whole-cluster granularity, never per-table, but can run synchronously or asynchronously as covered earlier. Trigger-based systems and SQL-broadcasting middleware, by contrast, operate per-table or per-query, but each brings its own hazards: trigger-based tools typically batch asynchronously, risking data loss on failover, while middleware that simply rebroadcasts SQL to every server can produce diverging results wherever a query touches something nondeterministic, like random() or CURRENT_TIMESTAMP. Notably, PostgreSQL doesn't ship a synchronous multimaster solution of its own at all — building one is left to application code or middleware, typically leaning on two-phase commit.",
