        title: 'Warm Standby vs Hot Standby: Two Genuinely Different Things',
        body: "These two terms sound like a matter of degree, but they describe a real functional split. A warm standby is a server that's continuously replaying WAL from the primary but cannot be queried at all while it does so — the only thing it can offer is a fast promotion later; trying to connect to one simply fails. A hot standby is the same replay process with one crucial addition: the hot_standby parameter, on by default, lets the server accept ordinary client connections and serve read-only queries while recovery is still actively running in the background. Turning that capability on requires wal_level to have been set to replica or logical back on the primary, since a lower level doesn't log enough information for the standby to reconstruct a consistent snapshot. Reaching that queryable state isn't instantaneous either — the server has to first replay far enough to hit a consistent recovery point, logging its own readiness message once it gets there, and only then does it genuinely function as a read-scaling target rather than just a disaster-recovery placeholder.",
