        body: "PostgreSQL hands every client connection its own dedicated backend process rather than multiplexing many client sockets through a shared pool of workers, and max_connections is simply a hard ceiling on how many of those processes can exist at once — nothing in the core server itself sits in front of that limit deciding which client gets a slot when demand spikes past it. That gap is exactly what an external connection pooler fills, and the de facto standard tool for the job is PgBouncer, a small, standalone proxy that presents itself to applications as an ordinary PostgreSQL server while internally maintaining and reusing a much smaller set of actual backend connections behind it. Because PgBouncer is a separate project maintained outside the core PostgreSQL distribution, its behavior — and in particular the different modes it can pool connections in — isn't described anywhere in PostgreSQL's own manual at all, which is exactly why understanding it means turning to PgBouncer's own documentation rather than the server's.",
